# 5-Minute Version — 7 Slides

---

## Slide 1 — Title
**"AI Agents: When to Use Them & How to Keep Them Safe"**
- Our internal LLM, our rules, our teams

---

## Slide 2 — Script vs. Agent (The Only Decision That Matters)

**Use a script when** the steps never change
**Use an agent when** the next step depends on what you just found

> A script does what you told it.
> An agent figures out what to do.

---

## Slide 3 — Real Examples on Our Teams

| Team | Script | Agent |
|---|---|---|
| DevOps | Rotate creds on schedule | Alert fires → investigate → remediate |
| Security | Parse logs to SIEM | Triage alert → correlate CVEs → score risk |
| Platform | Terraform on PR merge | Diagnose degraded service across 4 systems |

---

## Slide 4 — The Risk Without Governance

- Agent calls prod DB with no rate limit
- Approves its own remediation — no human sees it
- API key ends up in a log file
- Token costs spike across all teams with no visibility

**Agents with prod access and no guardrails are not automation — they're unpredictable.**

---

## Slide 5 — Four Governance Layers (Non-Negotiable)

1. **Identity** — one API key per team, rate-limited at the proxy, never in code
2. **Tool isolation** — DBA agents can't call Linux tools, Linux can't touch AD
3. **Policy gate** — rules engine (not the LLM) decides auto-execute vs. human approval
4. **Audit trail** — every agent run produces a retrievable trace, no exceptions

---

## Slide 6 — Who Owns What

**Platform team:** LLM proxy, policy rules, audit pipeline, tool schema registry

**Each team:** their agent code, their tools, their on-call responsibility for what their agent does

> No team deploys a write-capable agent without policy gate sign-off

---

## Slide 7 — The Ask

✅ Approve proxy + policy gate as shared platform infrastructure
✅ One agent owner per team
✅ Phase 1: read-only agents only — no autonomous actions until audit logging is live

**Bottom line:** We have the LLM. Governance is what makes it safe to actually use.

