Slide 2 — What We Already Have

Our Starting Point

	•	Internal LLM endpoint (self-hosted or private cloud)
	•	API keys distributed per team
	•	Existing scripts, runbooks, and automation
	•	The question isn’t whether to use AI — it’s where it adds real value vs. where it adds risk

Slide 3 — Two Tools, Two Jobs

Agent vs. Script — The Core Distinction

|            |Script                   |Agent                    |
|------------|-------------------------|-------------------------|
|Control flow|You write it             |LLM decides it           |
|Inputs      |Known, structured        |Unknown, variable        |
|Steps       |Fixed                    |Dynamic                  |
|Failure mode|Predictable              |Harder to audit          |
|Best for    |Repetitive, deterministic|Investigative, multi-step|




Slide 4 — When to Use a Script

Don’t reach for an agent when:

	•	The task has a fixed, known sequence of steps
	•	Inputs are always structured (a cron job, a webhook with a defined schema)
	•	You need 100% reproducibility for compliance or audit
	•	The task runs in under 5 seconds and never branches

Examples on our teams:

	•	Rotate credentials on a schedule



Slide 5 — When to Use an Agent

Reach for an agent when:

	•	The path to the answer depends on what you find along the way
	•	Tools need to be called in an order that can’t be hardcoded
	•	Context needs to be built up across multiple tool results before a decision
	•	A human would normally read, reason, then act

Examples on our teams:

Is the task sequence fixed?
  YES → Script

Does it require reading context before deciding the next step?
  YES → Does it need to call multiple tools conditionally?
    YES → Agent (LangGraph preferred)
    NO  → Simple LLM call (single prompt, no orchestration)

Does it need to take real-world action with consequences?
  YES → Agent + Policy Gate + Human-in-the-loop interrupt








